---
import Layout from "../../layouts/Layout.astro";
import { projects } from "../../data/projects";
import ProjectGallery from "../../components/ProjectGallery.astro";

const project = projects.find(
    p => p.slug === "exhibition-pool"
);

if (!project) {
    throw new Error("Project not found");
}
---

<Layout>

<div class="project-page">

    <a class="back-link" href="/projects">
        ← Back to Projects
    </a>

<section class="project-header">

    <div class="project-summary">

        <img
            src={project.companyLogo}
            alt={`${project.company} logo`}
            class={`project-company-logo ${project.companyLogoClass}`}
        />

        <h1>{project.title}</h1>


    </div>

    <div class={`project-hero-image ${project.heroImageClass}`}>

        <img
            src={project.heroImage}
            alt={project.title}
            class="project-hero"
        />

    </div>

</section>

<hr class="experience-divider" />

<section>

    <h3 class="company-section-title">
        Overview
    </h3>

    <p>
        In preparation for Piscina Barcelona 2025, one of the world's leading trade fairs for the
        swimming pool industry, Dekobo set out to create a custom exhibition pool that would
        showcase its automatic pool cover systems in a realistic environment. I was entrusted
        with designing the complete structure and coordinating its production, from the initial
        concept through manufacturing.
    </p>

    <p>
        With only four months available before the exhibition, the project had to be completed
        alongside the company's busiest production season, making careful planning and close
        collaboration essential.
    </p>

</section>

<section>

    <h3 class="company-section-title">
        Project Development
    </h3>

    <p>
        The objective was to design an exhibition pool that would not only demonstrate
        Dekobo's submerged pool cover system but also reflect the company's design
        philosophy. Besides functionality, the pool needed to attract visitors, be transportable,
        and withstand repeated assembly and disassembly for future exhibitions.
    </p>

    <p>
        To create a visual connection with Dekobo's product portfolio, I incorporated the same
        Disegna wooden decking used on the Milano pool cover model, giving the exhibition
        pool a distinctive appearance while maintaining a consistent brand identity.
    </p>

    <p>
        One of the owner's primary requirements was to use transparent pool walls so
        visitors could observe the submerged cover system in operation. Achieving this while
        ensuring structural integrity, watertightness, and an attractive appearance became the
        project's greatest engineering challenge.
    </p>
    
    <h4>Structural Design and Manufacturing</h4>

    <p>
        The exhibition pool was designed as a two-piece assembly to simplify manufacturing,
        transportation, and installation.
    </p>

    <p>
        The lower section consisted of a welded steel base frame constructed from AISI 316 rectangular
        profiles. L-shaped profiles positioned and supported the upper pool structure,
        while four integrated wheels allowed the entire assembly to be moved easily around
        the exhibition hall. The base also incorporated a dedicated compartment for the
        electrical equipment controlling the submerged cover. To maintain the clean appearance
        of the wooden cladding, I designed a push-to-open access door that blended seamlessly
        into the surrounding panels.
    </p>

    <p>
        The upper section consisted of a polished AISI 316L stainless steel frame with
        transparent plexiglass side panels. Working closely with Dekobo's welding specialist, we
        developed a fastening solution that allowed the plexiglass panels to be replaced
        individually if damaged, significantly improving the serviceability and long-term
        usability of the exhibition pool.
    </p>

    <p>
        To facilitate transportation and installation, I also integrated concealed lifting points
        into the upper structure. These were hidden beneath the removable top covers of the
        corner columns, allowing the pool to be safely lifted without compromising its clean
        exterior appearance.
    </p>

    <h4>System Integration</h4>

    <p>
        To demonstrate the product under realistic operating conditions, the pool was
        equipped with one of Dekobo's submerged automatic pool cover systems. The cover
        displayed the full range of available slat colours, allowing visitors to compare the
        different options during live demonstrations.
    </p>

    <p>
        To further simulate a real swimming pool installation, I also designed an integrated
        staircase inside the pool, creating a more authentic presentation while demonstrating
        that the cover system could operate around typical pool features.
    </p>

</section>

<section>

    <h3 class="company-section-title">
        Outcome
    </h3>

    <p>
        The exhibition pool was successfully completed within the available four-month
        development period and delivered in time for Piscina Barcelona 2025.
    </p>

    <p>
        According to feedback from colleagues attending the exhibition, the installation
        attracted significant visitor attention and effectively showcased Dekobo's automatic
        pool cover technology. The project demonstrated the importance of combining
        engineering, manufacturing coordination, and product presentation to deliver a
        functional exhibition piece under demanding time constraints.
    </p>

</section>

<section>

    <h3 class="company-section-title">
        Gallery
    </h3>

    <ProjectGallery
        images={[
            {
                src: "/images/projects/exhibition-pool/gallery-1.jpg",
                alt: "Exhibition pool CAD concept",
                caption: "Initial CAD concept"
            },
            {
                src: "/images/projects/exhibition-pool/gallery-2.jpg",
                alt: "Exhibition pool CAD assembly",
                caption: "Final CAD assembly"
            },
            {
                src: "/images/projects/exhibition-pool/gallery-3.jpg",
                alt: "Exhibition pool CAD render",
                caption: "Rendered CAD assembly"
            },
            {
                src: "/images/projects/exhibition-pool/gallery-4.jpg",
                alt: "Exhibition pool physical structure",
                caption: "Welded, assembled structure"
            },
            {
                src: "/images/projects/exhibition-pool/gallery-5.jpg",
                alt: "Exhibition pool physical structure",
                caption: "Welded, assembled structure"
            },
            {
                src: "/images/projects/exhibition-pool/gallery-6.jpg",
                alt: "Exhibiton pool with wooden paneling",
                caption: "Assembled pool with the wooden paneling"
            },
            {
                src: "/images/projects/exhibition-pool/gallery-7.jpg",
                alt: "Exhibition pool at expo",
                caption: "Pool presented at the expo"
            },
            {
                src: "/images/projects/exhibition-pool/video-thumb.jpg",
                video: "/images/videos/exhibition-pool/exhibition-pool.MP4",
                alt: "Video of testing the exhibition pool cover",
                caption: "Testing"
            },
            
        ]}
    />

</section>

{project.references && (

<section>

    <h3 class="company-section-title">
        References
    </h3>

    <div class="project-references">

        {project.references.map(reference => (

            <a
                href={reference.url}
                target="_blank"
                rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
                {reference.text} →
            </a>

        ))}

    </div>

</section>

)}

</div>

</Layout>